SIMPLE: import
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Import
<hw>Im*port"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Imported</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Importing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>importare</ets> to
bring in, to occasion, to cause; pref. <ets>im-</ets> in +
<ets>portare</ets> to bear. Sense 3 comes through F.
<ets>importer</ets>, from the Latin. See <er>Port</er> demeanor.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring in from abroad; to introduce from without;
especially, to bring (wares or merchandise) into a place or country from
a foreign country, in the transactions of commerce; -- opposed to
<recipr>export</recipr>. <as>We <ex>import</ex> teas from China, coffee
from Brazil, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To carry or include, as meaning or intention; to
imply; to signify.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Every petition . . . doth . . . always <qex>import</qex> a
multitude of speakers together.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be of importance or consequence to; to have a
bearing on; to concern.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have a motion much <qex>imports</qex> your good.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If I endure it, what <qex>imports</qex> it you?</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To denote; mean; signify; imply; indicate;
betoken; interest; concern.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Import</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Import
<hw>Im*port"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To signify; to purport; to be
of moment.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧For that . . . <xex>importeth</xex> to the
work.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Import</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Import
<hw>Im"port</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Merchandise imported, or brought into a country from without its
boundaries; -- generally in the plural, opposed to
<recipr>exports</recipr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I take the <qex>imports</qex> from, and not the exports to, these
conquests, as the measure of these advantages which we derived from
them.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which a word, phrase, or document contains as
its signification or intention or interpretation of a word, action,
event, and the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Importance; weight; consequence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Most serious design, and the great <qex>import</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Importable</ent>⟦br⟧
